dd-d64ea32e227d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ]; Jennifer A.=C2=A0Zimmer,=C2=A0MD [ https://link.sbstck.com/redir=
ect/b47b0647-4a5d-4631-bcb0-119cf33252d2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]1 [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/b47b=
0647-4a5d-4631-bcb0-119cf33252d2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]; Cynthia D.=C2=A0Evans,=C2=A0PhD [ https://link.=
sbstck.com/redirect/effb684d-33eb-47bf-b9f8-0d1e8c7f040b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]1 [ https://link.sbstck.c=
om/redirect/effb684d-33eb-47bf-b9f8-0d1e8c7f040b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]; et al in JAMA
Among participants with early symptomatic Alzheimer disease and amyloid and=
 tau pathology, donanemab significantly slowed clinical progression at 76 w=
eeks in those with low/medium tau and in the combined low/medium and high t=
au pathology population.
Alzheimer=E2=80=99s research is another area that comes up often in the Wee=
kly Dose. It=E2=80=99s a topic near and dear to our heart, as our grandmoth=
er suffered from a pretty horrible case of it and members of our family are=
 at higher risk of developing it. Packy=E2=80=99s fear of Alzheimer=E2=80=
=99s and memory loss is what motivated him to write in the first place!
So we=E2=80=99re excited when findings like this are published. The NYT has=
 a solid summary here [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/00abc13a-dea5-428a=
-8c5b-0096dd881ad3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ], but the gist is that a treating Alzheimer=E2=80=99s as early =
as possible =E2=80=94 when symptoms and brain pathology are mildest =E2=80=
=94 provides a better chance of slowing cognitive decline. The study found =
that patients taking the drug donanemab can modestly slow the progression o=
f memory and thinking problems.
There=E2=80=99s no cure to Alzheimer=E2=80=99s but it=E2=80=99s becoming in=
creasingly clear that early detection and treatment provide the most hopefu=
l path to reducing decline and increasing healthspan.=20
(5) The Prospects of Molecular Manufacturing [ https://link.sbstck.com/redi=
rect/1b272ade-fe70-4c21-b9cc-d5389e38f84d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA=
_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Anna-Sofia Lesiv [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/68f2d5e9-651a-4148-a74e=
-7ac7f220dbab?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ] for Contrary
Of course, atomic or molecular scale manufacturing wouldn=E2=80=99t just re=
volutionize domestic life, it would have consequences across all domains of=
 industry with massive implications for chemistry, material science, constr=
uction, medicine, and biology writ large. Two prominent thinkers exploring =
molecular machinery, J. Storrs Hall and Robert Freitas, estimated [ https:/=
/link.sbstck.com/redirect/a6372061-0c4e-4a4a-803f-e89f032f517a?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that =E2=80=9Cmatu=
re nanotechnology could replicate the entire capital stock of the United St=
ates =E2=80=93 =E2=80=98every single building, factory, highway, railroad, =
bridge, airplane, train, automobile, truck, and ship=E2=80=99 =E2=80=93 in =
a mere week.=E2=80=9D
Packy here. At this point, you know how much I love J. Storrs Hall=E2=80=99=
s Where is My Flying Car? [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/82a1f605-fdd1-=
43c9-a96b-3a3eed469cf7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] In it, Hall predicts the coming of the Second Atomic Age, =
brought about by a trio of technologies: nuclear energy, AI, and nanotechno=
logy.=20
Hall believes that nuclear energy can provide the power needed to run large=
-scale nanotech manufacturing facilities. AI can be used to design and cont=
rol these facilities, as well as to develop new nanotech products. Nanotech=
 can then be used to create new materials, devices, and systems that can so=
lve some of the world's most pressing problems.
We talk about nuclear energy and AI a bunch in Not Boring, but when I was l=
istening to a conversation between Hall and Eric Jorgenson the other day, I=
 realized that I had no idea what was going on in the world of non-bio nano=
tech.=20
Then, the very next day, BAM. Contrary=E2=80=99s Anna-Sofia Lesiv [ https:/=
/link.sbstck.com/redirect/68f2d5e9-651a-4148-a74e-7ac7f220dbab?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] shared the best pr=
imer we=E2=80=99ve found on molecular manufacturing, covering its history, =
technology landscape, and potential future use cases.
We=E2=80=99re still a few decades away from precision manufacturing at the =
atomic level, Anna-Sofia claims, but advancements in molecular manufacturin=
g are already pushing boundaries in everything from chip to cellular design=
=2E
And while we may be a few decades out, the potential of nano-scale manufact=
urer =E2=80=94 ie the ability to design and build basically anything in a l=
ab =E2=80=94 is so enormous that it merits attention today.
Read this one, and then go read everything that Anna-Sofia writes in Founda=
tions & Frontiers [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/242c0fb6-5710-41c2-a94=
6-0bbfe17c7fb7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ]. She=E2=80=99s one of my favorite writers out there right now. One=
 of the best ways to make people realistically optimistic about the future =
is to help them understand the tech, and Anna-Sofia=E2=80=99s deep tech exp=
lanations are both in-depth and approachable, a hard balance to pull off.=
=20
Bonus: Ezra CEO Emi Gal on Not Boring Founders=20
A few weeks ago, Packy wrote a deep dive on Ezra [ https://link.sbstck.com/=
redirect/18d25ee1-fe3a-4e93-a569-caa019605b28?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the startup using screening to cat=
ch cancer when it=E2=80=99s most treatable. A ton of you signed up to get y=
our own Ezra screening [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/82f8a164-518f-43b=
d-9dc1-4283cc6d3781?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ] (saving lives over here with our little newsletter) and many =
more reached out saying how happy you were that Ezra exists and asking foll=
ow-up questions. So Packy had Ezra=E2=80=99s CEO Emi Gal on Not Boring Foun=
ders to dive a little deeper and keep spreading the good word. Fuck cancer.=
=20
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tu=
esday.
Thanks for reading,
Dan + Packy

