es, and very rarely do I find it on the front pages. I have to dig. Doom se=
lls, but those headlines are only part (the less interesting one) of the st=
ory.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 2=
6px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The other big learning is just how steady, =
and now accelerating, progress has been for humans over the last 200-300 ye=
ars. Almost all measures of quality of life have improved over the last few=
 decades &#8212; not just for rich Americans, but for humanity as whole. It=
&#8217;s easy to look at the world in front of you and think, &#8220;Things=
 were so much better back then.&#8221; The reality is that for the first 30=
0,000 years of human existence things just weren&#8217;t that much </span><=
em>different &#8220;</em><span>back then.&#8221; And for the last 200 years=
, things were objectively </span><em>worse </em><span>&#8220;back then.&#82=
21;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">We have our problems, but I have never been=
 more confident in the upward slope of progress than I am today, after 52 e=
ditions of covering all of the amazing things we humans can pull off.</p><p=
